  "verdict": "The BMW M3 Competition wins this comparison by a meaningful margin. Its combination of engine character, chassis balance, and daily usability is unmatched. The Cadillac CT4-V Blackwing earns a strong second place — its Blackwing V8 delivers emotion the M3's turbo six cannot. The Mercedes-AMG C63 S E Performance disappoints: its hybrid powertrain adds weight and complexity without improving the driving experience.",

  "pros": "BMW M3: best chassis balance, strongest resale value. Cadillac CT4-V: best engine sound, best value. Mercedes C63: most powerful on paper",
  "cons": "BMW M3: expensive, firm ride. Cadillac CT4-V: dated interior, smaller dealer network. Mercedes C63: heavy hybrid system, highest price, worst fuel economy",

  "bodyText": "Three of the most anticipated sports sedans of 2025 face off at our test track. The BMW M3 Competition, Mercedes-AMG C63 S E Performance, and Cadillac CT4-V Blackwing represent three very different philosophies for what a performance sedan should be. BMW stakes its claim on refinement and balance. The M3 feels engineered to a consistent standard — every system works in harmony, nothing feels like an afterthought. The S58 engine is turbocharged but rev-happy, producing 503 horsepower while maintaining the character that made previous M3s legendary. Cadillac swims against the electrification tide with the CT4-V Blackwing's naturally aspirated 4.2-liter twin-turbocharged V8. At 668 horsepower it is the most powerful car here, and its exhaust note is genuinely magnificent — a sound that neither the BMW's turbo six nor the Mercedes hybrid system can replicate. Mercedes takes the most complex path with the C63 S E Performance. The 2.0-liter turbocharged four-cylinder paired with a rear-axle electric motor produces a combined 671 horsepower, but the system adds 500 pounds over the outgoing C63. At our skidpad, the Mercedes posted the worst lateral acceleration figure despite having the most power. Lap times told the same story: BMW 1:28.2, Cadillac 1:28.9, Mercedes 1:30.1. The BMW wins this comparison because it does everything well and nothing poorly.",

  "sections": [
    {
      "sectionTitle": "Performance comparison",
      "content": "BMW M3 Competition: 503hp, 0-60 in 3.4 seconds, lap time 1:28.2. Cadillac CT4-V Blackwing: 668hp, 0-60 in 3.5 seconds, lap time 1:28.9. Mercedes-AMG C63 S E Performance: 671hp combined, 0-60 in 3.3 seconds, lap time 1:30.1. Despite having the least power the BMW posted the fastest lap time, demonstrating that chassis balance matters more than peak horsepower.",
      "orderIndex": 1
    },
    {
      "sectionTitle": "Value comparison",
      "content": "BMW M3 Competition: $76,900 base, strong 58% 3-year residual. Cadillac CT4-V Blackwing: $91,495 base, average residuals but best performance per dollar. Mercedes-AMG C63 S E Performance: $84,900 base, weakest residuals in the group. For pure value the Cadillac offers the most performance per dollar. For total cost of ownership the BMW wins thanks to superior depreciation curves.",
